                <h2>Case Opening: The Account Manager's Monday Morning Breakdown</h2>
<p>Monday morning, 9 AM. An overseas e-commerce team's account manager, Xiaozhang, opens their laptop to find 12 unread emails, 87 unread messages in a pinned WeChat group, and 3 clients following up on account opening progress via Feishu.</p>
<p>"Did that Meta business account we opened for the client get approved last week?"</p>
<p>"When will the TikTok ad account top-up arrive?"</p>
<p>"We still have 3 Google accounts pending application. Clients have been waiting two days already."</p>
<p>Xiaozhang spent half an hour scrolling through chat history just to sort things out:</p>
<ul>
<li>Client A's Meta account was approved, but the client hadn't been notified</li>
<li>Client B's TikTok account top-up was delayed by 24 hours, affecting their promotional plan</li>
<li>Client C's Google account application materials were still being coordinated</li>
</ul>
<p>This isn't just Xiaozhang's predicament. Any team handling overseas ad account agency services will encounter similar chaos when managing more than 20 accounts.</p>
<h2>Problem Dissection: Three Fatal Flaws of Traditional Management</h2>
<h3>Flaw 1: Fragmented Information, Opaque Status</h3>
<p>Agency account opening involves multiple platforms (Meta, TikTok, Google, Pinterest, etc.), each with different application processes, review timelines, and required materials. The traditional approach uses Excel spreadsheets with communication scattered across WeChat, email, and Feishu.</p>
<p>The result: inconsistent spreadsheet versions, delayed updates, and "where exactly is the review at?" becoming the perpetual question.</p>
<h3>Flaw 2: Manual Follow-ups Lead to Missed Orders</h3>
<p>Ad platform review times range from hours to days. Manual tracking relies entirely on memory. Agency clients are numerous and diverse, with each client potentially needing 3-5 platform accounts managed simultaneously.</p>
<p>Missed orders mean direct consequences: client complaints, damaged trust, even lost business.</p>
<h3>Flaw 3: Disconnection Between Top-ups and Account Status</h3>
<p>Account opening is just the first step; subsequent top-ups, renewals, and credit adjustments all require synchronized follow-up. Many teams maintain separate spreadsheets for account management and finance—reconciliation errors are the norm, and balance alerts are nonexistent.</p>
<h2>Judgment: When Is a Systematic Kanban Necessary?</h2>
<p>Not every team needs kanban management. If your business meets any two of the following conditions, kanban becomes essential:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Managing more than 20 active accounts</strong> — Human memory can no longer keep track</li>
<li><strong>Serving more than 10 clients</strong> — Each client's account portfolio differs</li>
<li><strong>Involving 3+ ad platforms</strong> — Platform rules and progress vary</li>
<li><strong>Requiring multi-person collaboration</strong> — At least 2 people involved in account opening and top-ups</li>
</ol>
<h2>Action: How Kanban Reconstructs Agency Account Opening</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Categorize by Platform, One Card Per Account</h3>
<p>Kanban columns are set up by advertising platform: Meta, TikTok, Google Ads, Pinterest, etc. Each card represents one account, containing client name, account ID, application date, current status, and next action.</p>
<p>Cards flow between columns with status clearly visible at a glance.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Set Automated Trigger Rules</h3>
<p>Leveraging kanban tool automation capabilities:</p>
<ul>
<li>Auto-send internal notification when application is submitted</li>
<li>Auto-flag reminder if review exceeds 24 hours without update</li>
<li>Auto-trigger top-up alert when account balance falls below threshold</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Integrate with Finance System, Link Accounts to Top-up Records</h3>
<p>Kanban card details link to top-up records. Finance staff can directly view balance change trends for each account. During reconciliation, no need to scroll through spreadsheets—just one click to export reports.</p>
<h2>Results: One Month Comparison Data</h2>
<p>Returning to Xiaozhang's team. One month after implementing kanban management, they ran a simple comparison:</p>
<table>
